TY  - JOUR
AU  - O’Hara, Maureen
AU  - Saar, Gideon
AU  - Zhong, Zhuo
T1  - Relative Tick Size and the Trading Environment
PY  - 2019
Y1  - 2019/06/01
DO  - 10.1093/rapstu/ray009
JO  - The Review of Asset Pricing Studies
JA  - Rev Asset Pric Stud
VL  - 9
IS  - 1
SP  - 47
EP  - 90
SN  - 2045-9920
AB  - We investigate how and why relative tick sizes influence traders’ order strategies, and how this affects liquidity provision in the market. Using unique NYSE data, we find that a larger relative tick size benefits high-frequency trading (HFT) market makers: they leave orders in the book longer, trade more aggressively, and have higher profit margins. In a tick-constrained (tick-unconstrained) environment, larger relative ticks result in greater (less) depth, which is consistent with greater adverse selection coming from increased undercutting of limit orders by informed HFT market makers.Received October 12, 2017; editorial decision August 21, 2018 by Editor Thierry Foucault.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rapstu/ray009
ER  - 



